Let me explain briefly. Each product‐sale is a “deal” where, if the product is high quality (which happens about 1/3 of the time), you net $20,000 (since the product is worth $30,000 to you but you pay $10,000), and if it’s low quality (about 2/3 of the time) you lose $10,000. In a vacuum this gives an expected net value of

  (1/3 × $20,000) + (2/3 × –$10,000) = $6,667 – $6,667 = $0.

You are given additional public information: so far 3 buyers got “buy” recommendations, and among their purchases only 1 turned out to be high‑quality. That exactly reflects the base rate (1/3) for a high‑quality product. In other words, although Alice is “recommending” buying the product, the statistics show that whenever you are offered a product the chance of it being high quality remains 33.33%. Thus, the “deal” offers exactly zero net expected profit. Under risk neutrality you’d be indifferent; many might follow the (nonnegative‐expected value) recommendation and buy. In our answer we choose “yes.”
